This has the logic of an all-too-familiar anxiety-fuelled dream: the kind of dream where you're trapped in place and find yourself unable to move quicker than a strolling pace, despite wanting to run or escape. This hits all the right (wrong) weirdness and imagery notes, but was hard to follow in places (specifically Log 2) despite its clear and consistent clinical tone. Log 3's slow-rising and increasingly claustrophobic  and there's extra points for a competent MTF too.

The build-up was only capitalized on at the end of Log 3, so you almost lost me for a bit, but this is a definite +1 for me.








